'''Sarnya Marie Parker''', [[Order of Australia|OAM]]<ref name="oam">{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=886942&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Parker, Sarnya Marie, OAM|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> (born 6 June 1975)<ref name=2000-media-guide>{{cite book|title=Media guide : 2000 Sydney Paralympic Games|publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee|location=Sydney, Australia|year=2000}}</ref> is an Australian visually impaired [[paralympic]] [[tandem bicycle|tandem cyclist]]. She was born in the South Australian town of [[Loxton, South Australia|Loxton]].<ref name="2000-media-guide"/>Before she took up Paralympic tandem cycling, she was a nationally ranked top-ten [[pentathlon|pentathlete]].<ref name="advertiser">{{cite news|title=Pedal pals in hot seat|publisher=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]]|date=17 October 2000|page=70}}</ref>She won a gold medal in [[long jump]] at the 1999 [[FESPIC Games]] in Thailand.<ref name="2000-media-guide"/>

Eighteen months before the [[2000 Sydney Paralympics|2000 Sydney Games]], visually impaired Paralympic tandem cyclist [[Kieran Modra]] convinced her to switch from athletics to cycling because of the limited opportunities in the former sport for Paralympians.<ref>{{cite news|title=Track switch yields victory|publisher=[[The Age]]|date=21 October 2000|page=19|first=Melissa|last=Ryan}}</ref>He introduced her to his sister, [[Tania Modra]], despite Modra's lack of competitive cycling experience, and she became Parker's pilot.<ref name="advertiser"/>She won two gold medals for Australia with Modra at the 2000 Sydney Games in the 1&nbsp;km road race and 3000&nbsp;m pursuit, <ref name="advertiser"/><ref name=IPC-AUS>{{cite web|title=Athlete Search Results|url=http://www.paralympic.org/Sport/Results/search.html?npc=AUS&gender=all&medal=medals&sport=all&games=2000PG|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=2 October 2011}}</ref>for which she received a [[Order of Australia|Medal of the Order of Australia]];<ref name="oam"/> the pair broke the world record in both events.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another record as pair cut a golden swathe|publisher=[[The Age]]|date=22 October 2000|page=8|first=Melissa|last=Ryan}}</ref> In 2000, she received an [[Australian Sports Medal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=977605&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Parker, Sarnya: Australian Sports Medal|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref> In 2009, a walking trail on the riverfront of Loxton was named after her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-10-02/thousands-expected-at-loxton-show/1087754|title=Thousands expected at Loxton Show|publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]|date=2 October 2009|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>

